"In straight and level flight at a speed of 1.9 VS, the lift coefficient, expressed as a percentage of its maximum (CLMAX), would be:": "28 %",
"In straight and level flight at a speed of 1.8 VS, the lift coefficient, expressed as a percentage of its maximum (CLMAX), would be:\n\n>>> A) 31 %": "31 %",
"Whilst maintaining straight and level flight with a lift coefficient CL = 1, what will be the new approximate value of CL after the speed is increased by 41%?": "0.50",
"An aeroplane maintains straight and level flight while the speed is doubled. The change in lift coefficient will be:\n\n>>> A) × 0.25": "× 0.25",
"In straight and level flight at a speed of 1.3 VS, the lift coefficient, expressed as a percentage of its maximum (CLMAX), would be:": "59 %",
"Assuming ISA conditions and no compressibility effects, if an aeroplane maintains straight and level flight at the same angle of attack at two different altitudes, the:": "TAS is lower at the lower altitude.",
"Whilst maintaining straight and level flight with a lift coefficient CL = 1 what will be the new approximate value of CL after the speed is increased by 30%?\n\n>>> A) 0.60": "0.60",
"Refer to an aircraft with a CL of 0.35 during the cruise and a speed of 1.6 VS. What will be the CL if the speed is reduced to 1.1 VS?": "0.74",
"Refer to figure 081-90.\n1.32 VMD is shown by point...": "4",
"If you decelerate from 1.4 VS to 1.05 VS, the percentage increase in the lift coefficient (expressed as a percentage of CLMAX), would be:\n\n>>> A) 40 %": "40 %",
"If an aircraft is flying at 1.1 VS with CL of 1.22 and the aircraft increases the speed to 1.8 VS, what is the new CL?\n\n>>> A) 0.46": "0.46",
"In straight and level flight at a speed of 1.7 VS, the lift coefficient, expressed as a percentage of its maximum CLMAX, would be:": "35 %.",
"Refer to figure 081-94.\nImagine an aircraft in steady, straight, and level flight at a given speed and mass, represented by point A on the graph. If the angle of attack increases, the coefficient of lift (CL) also increases, moving the aircraft to point B on the graph. To maintain steady, straight, and level flight, the indicated airspeed should be (1) ___ to maintain the (2) ___ constant.\n(Note: Assume constant aircraft mass, no changes in configuration, and subsonic flight conditions.)": "(1) reduced; (2) lift.",
"Given:\nAirspeed\t230 kt\nCL\t0.3\n\nCalculate the new CL, if the airspeed is reduced to 200 kt:": "0.40",
"In straight and level flight at a speed of 1.2 VS, the lift coefficient, expressed as a percentage of its maximum (CLMAX), would be:": "69 %",
"If the airspeed is doubled, whilst maintaining the same control surface deflection the aerodynamic force on this control surface will:": "become four times greater.",
"Refer to figure 081-90.\nVS is shown by point...\n\n>>> A) 1": "1",
"An aircraft flying straight and level at 1.1 VS has a lift coefficient (CL) of 1.22. If it accelerates to 1.8 VS while maintaining level flight, what will the new CL be?\n\n>>> A) 0.46": "0.46",
"An aircraft is flying at 200 kt with a coefficient of lift of 0.6. ATC request the pilot to increase airspeed to 250 kt. What is the new coefficient of lift?": "0.38",
"An aircraft climbs to FL210 with a CAS of 150 kt. Once reaching FL210 it accelerates to cruise speed whilst maintaining the same heading and altitude. During the transition to cruise speed, what happens to the coefficient of lift?\n\n>>> A) Decreases": "Decreases",
"Refer to figure 081-90.\nVMP is shown by point...\n\n>>> A) 2": "2",
"Refer to figure 081-03.\nDuring a movement from point 2 to point 4 during straight and level flight,...\n\n>>> A) airspeed is decreasing.": "airspeed is decreasing.",
"Assuming standard atmospheric conditions, in order to generate the same amount of lift as altitude is increased, an aeroplane must be flown at:": "a higher TAS for any given angle of attack.",
