"The maneuvering speed VA is 260 kt. If weight is reduced by 20 % what is the new VA?\n\n>>> A) 232 kt": "232 kt",
"A pilot is conducting spins for training. After entering the spin, the speed is so high that the pilot is concerned and pulls back the control column. During the pitch-up maneuver, the speed is much higher than VA but less than VNE. What can happen?\n\n>>> A) No limits are exceeded, since we're under VNE": "No limits are exceeded, since we're under VNE",
"Consider VMO and VC speeds and select the correct statement.": "VMO must NOT be greater than VC",
"What is the maximum negative load factor for the calculation of Vd in clean configuration for a transport aircraft?\n\n>>> A) 0 g": "0 g",
"Define VC:\n\n>>> A) VC is a speed which is chosen by the designer and which is used to assess the strength requirements in cruise.": "VC is a speed which is chosen by the designer and which is used to assess the strength requirements in cruise.",
"You are flying a crop duster in the utility category with a VSO of 55 kt and a VS1 of 70 kt. What is the VA speed for this aircraft?": "147 kt",
"Consider an aircraft with a 1 g stalling speed of 70 kt and limit load factor of 2.5. VA will be...": "111 kt",
"An aircraft has a manoeuvring speed (VA) of 108 kt, at a mass of 1 500 kg. Calculate the new VA speed at the MTOM of 2 064 kg:\n\n>>> A) 127 kt": "127 kt",
"At what point does the +1G line initially cross the flight envelope on the manoeuvring load diagram?": "The +1G stall speed",
"EASA CS-23 and CS-25 specify the applicable requirements for an aircraft's design manoeuvring speed (VA). VA is an equivalent airspeed (EAS) and remains applicable for airplanes with conventional flight controls. Nonetheless, this value can become unreliable at high altitudes, because:": "the wings may enter a shock stall if flying at the low-altitude VA since the aeroplane will exceed MCRIT.",
"What can be obtained from a manoeuvring-load diagram?": "Maximum load factor at stall",
"An airplane is flying at 1.4 VA and it decreases to 1.1 VA, by what percentage does the CL increase?\n\n>>> A) 62 %": "62 %",
"If the manoeuvring speed (VA) of a small single engine airplane is 123 kt and the mass is 2 300 lb, what will be the manoeuvring speed with a mass of 1 900 lb?\n\n>>> A) 112 kt": "112 kt",
"Define and describe the purpose of VC": "It is called Design Cruise Speed and used to show compliance with gust intensity loading.",
"The design speed for the maximum gust intensity is:": "VB",
"According to CS-23, what is the maximum allowable value of VNE?": "0.9 x VD",
"A CS-23 aircraft has a VA of 181 kt at a mass of 5.7 t. Calculate the VA for a mass of 4.1 t.": "154 kt",
"Which factor should be taken into account when determining VA?": "The limit load factor.",
"The positive manoeuvring limit load factor for an aeroplane in the aerobatic category in the clean configuration may not be more than:": "+6.00 g",
"Which of the following describes VA?\n\n>>> A) It is the design manoeuvring speed. At speeds at or faster than VA, rapid and/or full control deflection should be avoided due to risk of damage to aircraft.": "It is the design manoeuvring speed. At speeds at or faster than VA, rapid and/or full control deflection should be avoided due to risk of damage to aircraft.",
"The positive manoeuvring limit load factor for a large jet transport aeroplane with flaps extended is:\n\n>>> A) 2.0 g": "2.0 g",
"Maximum Operating Mach Number (MMo) is ________ the Design Dive Mach Number (MD) or Flight Demonstrated Design Dive Mach Number (MDF).\n\n>>> A) ...sufficiently less than...": "...sufficiently less than...",
"An aircraft has a stalling speed of 173 kt, at 5.4 tonnes. Calculate the new stalling speed at a mass of 4.7 tonnes:": "161 kt",
"Refer to EASA CS-25 manoeuvring flight envelope. The negative manoeuvring limit load factor for a large jet transport aeroplane is:": "-1 g",
"Refer to figure 081-114.\nWhat is indicated by the red marking 'A'?": "VS1G",
"Increasing the aircraft mass causes VA to (1) ___ and the design limit load factor to (2) ___.": "(1) increase; (2) remain the same.",
"Calculate the VA for an aerobatic aeroplane with a VS0 of 48 kt and a VS1 of 57 kt.": "140 kt",
"The stall speed lines in the manoeuvring load diagram originate from a point where the:\n\n>>> A) speed = 0, load factor = 0.": "speed = 0, load factor = 0.",
"What is the relation of VMO relative to VC?": "VMO ≤ VC",
"Given:\n \nVA:\t 133 kt\nVNE:\t 185 kt\nGreen arc:\t 73 kt - 177 kt \nWhite arc:\t 53 kt - 104 kt\n\nDetermine the limit load factor from the given airspeed indicator information:": "3.3 G",
"You are flying a crop duster in the utility category with a VSO of 45 kt and a VS1 of 58 kt. What is the VA speed for this aircraft?": "122 kt",
"What can happen to the aeroplane structure flying at a speed just exceeding VA?": "It may suffer permanent deformation if the elevator is fully deflected upwards.",
"Determine VA for an aerobatic airplane with a VS0 of 41 kt and a VS1 of 56 kt.\n\n>>> A) 142 kt": "142 kt",
"Consider VMO and VC speeds and select the correct statement.\n\n>>> A) VMO must NOT be greater than 0.8 x VC": "VMO must NOT be greater than 0.8 x VC",
"Determine VA for an aerobatic airplane with a VS0 of 41 kt and a VS1 of 56 kt.": "137 kt",
"What may happen if the \"ultimate load factor\" is exceeded?": "Structural failure.",
"Given aircraft:\nUtility category\nVSO: 45 kt\nVS1: 54 kt\n\nDetermine VA:": "113 kt",
"All gust lines in the gust load diagram originate from a point where the:": "speed = 0, load factor = +1.",
