"What of the following lift curves will have a greater load factor?": "Steeper CL with high aspect ratio.",
"Which of the following is a correct design gust value factor applied in certification under EASA CS-25 for VB?\n\n>>> A) 66 ft/sec": "66 ft/sec",
"By how much would the gust load change for an aircraft flying at 40 000 ft, compared to the same aircraft flying at sea level, if the EAS remains the same for a given gust velocity?": "Half as much.",
"An aeroplane maintains straight and level flight at a speed of 1.8VS. If a vertical gust causes a load factor of 1.9, the load factor n caused by the same gust at a speed of 2VS would be:": "2.00",
"An aeroplane flying at 100 kt in straight and level flight is subjected to a disturbance that suddenly increases the speed by 20 kt. Assuming the angle of attack remains constant, the load factor will initially:": "increase to 1.44.",
"When flying at the design cruise speed (Vc) an aircraft should withstand vertical gusts up to...": "50 ft/sec",
"Which of these statements about the gust load factor on an aeroplane are correct or incorrect?\nWhen the wing area increases, the gust load factor decreases.\nWhen the EAS increases, the gust load factor increases.": "1) is incorrect, 2) is correct.",
"Which of these statements about the gust load factor on an aeroplane are correct or incorrect?\nWhen the slope of the lift versus angle of attack curve decreases, the gust load factor increases.\nWhen the wing loading decreases, the gust load factor decreases.": "1) is incorrect, 2) is incorrect.",
"You are flying at FL380 and encounter a thunderstorm up ahead. You can’t fly around it, what do you do?\n\n>>> A) Fly at your VRA speed.": "Fly at your VRA speed.",
"An aeroplane in straight and level flight at 300 kt is subjected to a sudden disturbance in speed. Assuming the angle of attack remains constant initially and the load factor reaches a value of approximately 1.69:": "the speed will have increased by 90 kt.",
"Which of the following is a correct design gust value factor applied in certification under EASA CS-25 for VC?\n\n>>> A) 50 ft/sec": "50 ft/sec",
"When is the wing load at its maximum considering the aeroplane takes off with its wing tanks filled with fuel and just its centre tank empty?": "On landing",
