"Which of these statements about the gust load factor on an aeroplane are correct or incorrect?\nWhen the mass decreases, the gust load factor increases.\nWhen the altitude decreases, the gust load factor increases.": "1) is correct, 2) is correct.",
"An aeroplane maintains straight and level flight at a speed of 1.7VS. If a vertical gust causes a load factor of 1.85, the load factor n caused by the same gust at a speed of 2VS would be:": "2.00",
"An aeroplane flying at 200 kt in straight and level flight is subjected to a disturbance that initially result in a load factor of 1.44. Assuming the angle of attack remains constant, the...": "speed initially increases by 40 kt.",
"Which of the following is the speed for maximum gust?": "VB",
"What is true about the slope of the lift curve in a gust load diagram and its impact on the gust load factor for a given gust speed and aircraft true airspeed?\n\n>>> A) The steeper the slope of the lift curve, the greater the gust load factor.": "The steeper the slope of the lift curve, the greater the gust load factor.",
"An aeroplane flying at 200 kt in straight and level flight is subjected to a disturbance that suddenly increases the speed by 100 kt. Assuming the angle of attack remains constant, the load factor will initially:\n\n>>> A) increase to 2.25.": "increase to 2.25.",
"What is the origin of the gust envelope?": "From the 1G point running through three reference speeds VB, VC and VD.",
"Which of the following is a correct design gust value factor applied in certification under EASA CS-25?\n\n>>> A) 25 ft/sec at VD.": "25 ft/sec at VD.",
"Refer to an aircraft in an unaccelerated straight and level flight with a lift coefficient (CL) of 0.47, and consider that a change in 1° of the angle of attack (AoA) changes the CL by 0.1. Therefore, a vertical gust that increases the angle of attack by 3°, leads to a load factor of:": "1.64",
