"During approach, a twin-engine propeller aircraft experiences a failure of the left engine. The pilot applies full power to the right engine to initiate a go-around. In this situation, what is the effect of flap deployment on the aircraft's performance and handling?": "Flaps increase drag and increase the roll to the left.",
"VMCA is the minimum speed at which directional control can be maintained when, amongst others:\nmaximum take-off thrust was set and is maintained on the remaining engines.\na sudden engine failure occurs on the most critical engine.\nflaps are in any position.\nthe gear is either up or down.\nthe aeroplane is either in or out of ground effect.\nThe combination that regroups all of the correct statements is:": "1, 2",
"Refer to a twin-eninge airplane with an engine failure. If the engines are mounted below the wings, an increase in engine thrust will cause the yawing moment to…": "increase.",
"A pilot is taking-off with a multi-engine airplane on a flooded runway. Suddenly the aircraft becomes uncontrollable because of significant yaw. The reason for this is most likely:": "Asymmetric thrust",
"If an engine fails on a twin engined aeroplane a yawing moment will appear. Which CG location will provide the least ability to oppose this yawing moment?\n\n>>> A) When the CG is located at the aft CG limit.": "When the CG is located at the aft CG limit.",
"A multi-engine aircraft is taking off from a wet runway. Suddenly, the aircraft becomes uncontrollable due to a severe yawing motion. This is...": "Asymmetric thrust",
"What is the most difficult situation to encounter an engine failure with a twin-engine propeller airplane?": "Aerodrome at low density altitude, critical engine failure at the point of go-around.",
"An airplane is encountering a left engine fire during the cruise phase. The crew manages to extinguish the fire, shut down the engine, and thereafter preparing the airplane for landing. While the airspeed is reduced, the pilot flying maintains wings level and constant thrust, but needs larger variations in rudder input to keep the desired direction. Why?": "The amount of sideslip increases as speed decreases, making the airflow arrive at the vertical stabiliser at a greater angle, thereby reducing the rudder’s effectiveness.",
"Given a multi engine aeroplane, which of the following combinations will give the least control problem during an engine failure?": "An aircraft with the left propeller turning clockwise and the right propeller turning anticlockwise.",
"Compare two similar twin-engine airplanes where the only difference is the direction of rotation of their propellers. Airplane A uses clockwise-rotating propellers and airplane B uses inward-rotating propellers. A left engine failure on both airplanes will result as follows:": "Airplane A will have the greatest yaw moment, and it will produce a yaw to the left.",
"Which of these statements about the limiting value of 5° bank angle during VMCA determination are correct or incorrect?\nAs the bank angle is decreased from 5° to 0°, the value of VMCA increases.\nAt any bank angle beyond 5°, VMCA will decrease correspondingly.": "1) is correct, 2) is incorrect.",
"During an engine failure with a twin-engine airplane, the pilot correctly banks towards the live engine and uses the rudder to counteract yaw. Which of the following conditions would be better in such a situation?": "A high airplane mass, due to greater rudder effectiveness from increased airflow over the control surface.",
"Which of the following statements with reference to the relationship between VMCG and CG location for a common airplane (e.g. A320 or B737) is correct?": "A forward CG decreases VMCG.",
"How is VMC affected by an increase in density altitude?\n\n>>> A) A decrease in thrust decreases VMC.": "A decrease in thrust decreases VMC.",
"Refer to an asymmetric flight. Yawing towards the live engine results in a sideslip and a side force on the fuselage:": "behind the CG and opposite to the rudder force.",
"Select the correct configuration for determining VMCL:\n\n>>> A) Landing flap, trimmed for all engines operating": "Landing flap, trimmed for all engines operating",
"What happens to the minimum control speeds in asymmetric thrust conditions when the density alititude increases?": "They decrease, due to less thrust being developed by the engines, and therefore control being able to be maintained at a lower CAS.",
"If a light twin-engine aeroplane experiences an engine failure and the pilot chooses not to feather the propeller, what will be the outcome?": "Control will be more difficult, and the climb gradient will be lower.",
"Refer to figure 081-85.\nYou are flying a twin-engine jet when the left engine fails. Clouds are present on the right side of the aircraft, and you want to stay clear of the clouds. Which control input combination is most appropriate to maintain safe flight and avoid the clouds?": "Use right rudder and right bank input to maintain heading and avoid the clouds.",
"What factors should the pilot be aware of when operating a multi-engine aircraft with left engine failure, resulting in a sideslip and the nose pointing to the right?\n\n>>> A) The angle of attack AoA of the fin increases when there is an increase in rudder input to the operating engine side of the aircraft.": "The angle of attack AoA of the fin increases when there is an increase in rudder input to the operating engine side of the aircraft.",
"When flying a twin-engine aircraft with the critical engine failed, the angle of attack of the fin will (1) ___ when making a slight bank toward the (2) ___ engine.": "(1) decrease; (2) operative.",
